[2]
From: erwin.jackson@green2.greenpeace.org
Date: Mon, 4-MAR-96 05:24:34 GMT
Frm: Erwin Jackson, Climate Impacts Unit, Greenpeace International.

River virus epidemic fear,' Sydney Morning Herald, 04.03.96.

Queensland and northern NSW were experiencing a Ross River Virus (RRV)
outbreak in near epidemic proportions, the Queensland Medical Laboratory
said yesterday.
Its consultant microbiologist Dr David Drummond, said the Barmah Forest
Virus (BFV) which was spread by the sample types of mosquito as RRV, was
also on the increase. Record early summer rains which increased mosquito
breeding areas, had contributed to the RRV upsurge. "Major epidemics are
usually associated with excess rainfall and the presence of large amounts
of surface water," Dr Drummond said in a statement.
Most cases of RRV in previous years had been recorded between Brisbane and
the Sunshine Coast. "Now, however, there has been a marked increase around
Gladstone, Goondiwindi and northern inland NSW following widespread
flooding," he said. Significant numbers of cases were also being found in
the Ipswich and Brisbane River Valley areas. "In fact, virtually all areas
of south-east and central Queensland are recording increased cases,
suggesting a widespread epidemic,' Dr Drummond said.
BFV cases had risen steadily in the past few years peaking each summer. It
produced the same symptoms as RRV - arthritis, rash, tiredness and fever -
and its geographical distribution was similar to that of RRV, he said.

